<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910226-0114</DOCNO><DOCID>910226-0114.</DOCID><HL>   Marketing andamp; Media:   Los Angeles Times to Halt   Sales to Certain Regions</HL><DATE>02/26/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE C21</SO><CO>   WNEWS TMC</CO><IN>MEDIA, PUBLISHING, BROADCASTING, ELECTRONIC PUBLISHING (MED)</IN><LP>   LOS ANGELES -- Times Mirror Co., stung by the recession,said its flagship Los Angeles Times newspaper would haltdistribution in 10 central California counties and four majorcities in Arizona, Utah and Nevada.   &quot;We didn't sell advertising in those areas,&quot; said CarolynHom, a spokeswoman for the newspaper, which has dailycirculation of 1.2 million. &quot;Any time you are just sellingnewspapers without advertising, it is going to be at a loss.&quot;</LP><TEXT>   The cuts in newsstand and delivery sales represent a shiftfor the newspaper, which has successfully sought to boostcirculation in recent years. Earlier this month, however,Times Mirror reported that fourth-quarter net income dropped38%. Also, it said that the Los Angeles Times would drop itsafternoon edition because of declining readership. Ms. Homsaid the newspaper will focus on Southern Californiacirculation. The newspaper is halting its circulation inReno, Nev.; Phoenix and Tucson, Ariz.; and Salt Lake City.   Ms. Hom declined to say how much readership might be lostbut said it represents &quot;a very small percentage of ourcirculation.&quot; She said the cuts will go into effect nextmonth and that no other cutbacks are planned.   Meanwhile, the company said that Jeffrey S. Klein, 37years old, was named president of the newspaper's SanFernando Valley and Ventura County editions. He succeedsJeffrey S. Hall, 39, who was named special assistant toRichard T. Schlosberg III, who is the group vice president,newspapers, for Times Mirror.</TEXT></DOC>